<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="168" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,798,1559,1907]" lastBlockId="6.[835,1444,228,1907]" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">
Two adult specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Claassen" authorityYear="1923" box="[416,535,1740,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Leuctridae" genus="Leuctra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis box="[416,535,1740,1763]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">L. truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected during this study. It has been collected in cold water streams in most of northeastern North America (Harper &amp; Hynes 1971a). This species was first recorded from the Canadian Maritimes in 
<collectorName box="[835,1054,228,252]" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">Catamaran Brook</collectorName>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1075,1273,228,252]" country="Canada" name="New Brunswick" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">New Brunswick</collectingRegion>
(
<collectorName box="[1297,1405,228,252]" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">Giberson</collectorName>
&amp; 
<collectorName box="[835,925,264,288]" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">Garnett</collectorName>
1996). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Claassen" authorityYear="1923" box="[1023,1212,265,288]" class="Insecta" family="Leuctridae" genus="Leuctra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis box="[1023,1212,265,288]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="168">Leuctra truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a late summer species, and the 
<specimenCount box="[1037,1165,300,324]" pageId="6" pageNumber="168" type="adult">two adults</specimenCount>
collected in this study were collected in emergence traps between 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:9B0687E0FFC1467EFF68B8D4FC3D1BA7:1670602DFFC1467EFA9EBF23FA421B43" box="[1355,1443,336,360]" name="August" pageId="6" pageNumber="168" stateProvince="New Brunswick">August</location>
and October.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
